Poll: What computer software do you often use for statistics or scientific calculation? R, SPSS, Excel, python, MatLab…

1.3.2 What is R

R is a programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing. The R language is widely used among statisticians and data miners for developing statistical software and data analysis. Polls, data mining surveys, and studies of scholarly literature databases show substantial increases in popularity; as of April 2021, R ranks 16th in the TIOBE index, a measure of popularity of programming languages.

— Wikipedia: R (programming language)

In short, R is a language, with which you can talk to your computer.

1.3.5 RStudio

Demonstration: RStudio interface.

Use hotkeys:

  • ctrl + enter (run the line where the cursor is)
  • TAB (complete names of functions and objects)
  • F1 (get help)
  • shift + alt + k (see all shortcuts)

Create an R project:

  • File - New project - New directory - New project
  • Organize your R scripts and products in a project:
  • Save your related files in the project folder
  • Always start your work from the .Rproj file

Create a script (.R):

  • File - New File - R Script. Hotkey ctrl+shift+N

1.3.6 Statistics/calculation with R

  • Download the demo dataset iris.csv from the LMO.
  • Save it in your R project.

Figure 1.5: Iris 

# Import data
iris = read.csv("iris.csv")
iris <- read.csv("iris.csv")

# Simple Calculation
mean(iris$Petal.Length)

# Summarized data
summary(iris)

# ANOVA
myaov <- aov(Sepal.Length ~ Species,
            data = iris)
summary(myaov)

# Insert a column
iris$Sepal.Length.m <- iris$Sepal.Length / 100

# Export data
write.csv(iris, "iris2.csv")

1.3.7 Graphing with R

# Basic
plot(x = iris$Petal.Width, 
     y = iris$Petal.Length)
boxplot(iris$Sepal.Length)

# Install a package
install.packages("ggplot2")
# Load a package
library("ggplot2")
# Use functions
ggplot(iris,aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width))+ 
  geom_point()

# Install a package
install.packages("GGally")
# Load a package
library("GGally")
# Use a function
ggpairs(iris[, 2:6])
ggpairs(iris[, 2:6], 
        aes(color = Species, alpha = 0.1))

1.3.8 Modeling with R

# A linear model
mylm <- lm(iris$Petal.Width ~ iris$Petal.Length)
mylm
summary(mylm)

# Visualization
plot(x = iris$Petal.Length, 
     y = iris$Petal.Width)
abline(mylm)

ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length,Petal.Width))+ 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Show time: a paper

# basic
demo(nlm)
demo(lm.glm)

demo(gradArrows1) # Gradient descent method

1.5.2 Air Quality

The New York Air Quality dataset shows daily air quality measurements in New York, May to September 1973. The measurements include mean ozone in parts per billion from 1300 to 1500 hours at Roosevelt Island, solar radiation in Langleys in the frequency band 4000–7700 Angstroms from 0800 to 1200 hours at Central Park, average wind speed in miles per hour at 0700 and 1000 hours at LaGuardia Airport, maximum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit at La Guardia Airport.

  • Download the data file airquality.csv from LMO.
  • Import it into R as a data frame.
  • Summarize the dataset.
  • Make a scatter plot with two numeric variables, and add a linear fitted line.

1.5.3 ENV221 Students
